@@ -52,8 +52,10 @@ password, then place the resulting hashes under the corresponding
 `password_hash` keys. The phone app uses the original `mhr` plaintext password;
 it does not use the hash.
 
-The generated runtime server configuration is a SOPS template owned by the
-`ntfy-sh` service user. Password hashes therefore do not enter the Nix store.
+The bcrypt hashes are injected through the native NixOS
+`services.ntfy-sh.environmentFile` option using a SOPS template owned by the
+`ntfy-sh` service user. The regular server settings remain in the generated
+NixOS configuration, while the hashes do not enter the Nix store.
 
 ## Topics and ACLs
 
@@ -94,15 +96,15 @@ The corresponding SOPS key would be `ntfy/users/luise/password_hash`.
 
 ## Declarative authentication behavior
 
-The server configuration contains `auth-users` and `auth-access`. ntfy creates
-or updates those users and ACLs when `ntfy-sh.service` starts, and removes
-previously provisioned entries that are no longer declared. There is no separate
-provisioning unit and no administrative CLI lifecycle to coordinate.
+The service receives `NTFY_AUTH_USERS` and `NTFY_AUTH_ACCESS` through its
+SOPS-managed environment file. ntfy creates or updates those users and ACLs
+when `ntfy-sh.service` starts, and removes previously provisioned entries that
+are no longer declared. There is no separate provisioning unit and no
+administrative CLI lifecycle to coordinate.
 
-The authentication database remains at `/var/lib/ntfy-sh/user.db`. The service
-uses a static system user so its `StateDirectory` consistently resolves to
-`/var/lib/ntfy-sh` instead of switching between public and `DynamicUser`
-private-state paths.
+The authentication database remains at `/var/lib/ntfy-sh/user.db`. The module
+keeps the native NixOS service and its `StateDirectory`, but disables
+`DynamicUser` so the state path stays consistently at `/var/lib/ntfy-sh`.
 
